Section 1:
1 L.D. 492
2 Date: (Filing No. H- )
3 JUDICIARY
5 STATE OF MAINE
6 HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES
7 132ND LEGISLATURE
8 FIRST SPECIAL SESSION
9 COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to H.P. 321, L.D. 492, “RESOLUTION,
10 Proposing an Amendment to the Constitution of Maine to Provide for Parental Rights”
11 Amend the resolution by striking out the title and substituting the following:
12 'RESOLUTION, Proposing an Amendment to the Constitution of Maine to Protect
13 the Fundamental Rights of Parents'
14 Amend the resolution in that part designated "Constitution, Art. I, §26" in §26 in the
15 last 2 lines (page 1, lines 9 and 10 in L.D.) by striking out the following: ", absent abuse or
16 neglect by the parent or guardian or criminal acts by the minor" and inserting the following:
17 'unless the infringement is narrowly tailored to achieve a compelling state interest,
18 including the State's compelling interests in the prevention of child abuse or neglect, the
19 prevention of criminal conduct by minors and the rehabilitation of minors who have been
20 found to have committed criminal conduct'
21 Amend the resolution by relettering or renumbering any nonconsecutive Part letter or
22 section number to read consecutively.
23 SUMMARY
2244 This amendment, which is the minority report of the committee, clarifies that the State,
2255 its political subdivisions and all governmental entities may not infringe on the authority of
2266 parents to direct the upbringing, education and care for the physical, mental and spiritual
2277 health of their children unless the infringement is narrowly tailored to achieve a compelling
2288 state interest, including the State's compelling interest in the prevention of child abuse or
2299 neglect, the prevention of criminal conduct by minors and the rehabilitation of minors who
3300 have been found to have committed criminal conduct.
3311 FISCAL NOTE REQUIRED
3322 (See attached)
Page 1 - 132LR1308(02)
COMMITTEE AMENDMENT
